#### II.

### ATHENAGORAS

<span class="small">*Libellus pro Christianis*, <span
id="fr_508"></span>[1](#fn_508) xxviii.; Schwartz (E..md), p. 57, 24
(Leipzig, 1891). <span id="fr_509"></span>[2](#fn_509.md)</span>

<span class="smallcaps">Athenagoras</span> was acquainted with a Greek
literature circulated under the name of Hermes Trismegistus, to whom he
refers as authority for his euhemeristic contention that the gods were
once simply men. <span id="fr_510"></span>[3](#fn_510.md)

